The Berlin2CD pBridge now completes coherent NULL descriptors and
reversible CFGW register writes on hardware. Exercise the first read-only
NAND function without exposing page data or an MTD.

Build an eight-instruction, 64-byte BCM function from the modern driver's
READID definitions. Require the NFC command handshake before submission,
write all four NDCB words, wait for the data handshake, and copy eight
bytes from NDDB into 32-bit-addressable coherent memory.

Bound every semaphore and engine wait. Require and pop the NFC data
completion semaphore, require the command and data semaphores to return
empty, and check ND_RUN, CMDD, pBridge busy state and BCM error state.
Keep the coherent buffers managed for the device lifetime so a timed-out
descriptor is never raced by PIO identification or freed memory.

Accept only the confirmed Micron prefix and retain the result for
comparison with the later PIO READID. Any transport failure reuses the
existing probe gate, leaving the driver bound while skipping NAND-core
identification.

This remains probe-only. It does not read pages or OOB, enable ECC or the
randomizer, register an MTD, erase, or program NAND.

